# BernsteinРђЊLagarias Рђћ The 3x+1 map and the 2-adic shift (BL96, ┬Д1)

Daniel J. Bernstein and Jeffrey C. Lagarias, *The 3x+1 conjugacy map*, Canadian Journal of
Mathematics **48** (1996), no. 6, 1154РђЊ1169.

Foundation file for the `BL` corpus. It formalises the opening statements of the paper (┬Д1): the
3x+1 function `(1.1)`, its extension to the 2-adic integers, the 2-adic shift map `(1.2)`, the
ergodic theory of the 3x+1 map, and the topological conjugacy `(1.3)` between the two maps.

## The 3x+1 function (1.1)

The **3x+1 function** is `T(x) = (3x+1)/2` for `x РЅА 1 (mod 2)` and `T(x) = x/2` for `x РЅА 0 (mod 2)`,
on the integers `Рёц`. On `РёЋ` this is `CC.T` (from `CC.Parity`, which re-exports
`CC.Terras`), written in the compact form `T n = (n┬и3^{X n} + X n) / 2` with `X n = n mod 2`. The
parity-vector machinery of `CC.Parity` (`V`, `E_vec`, `q`, `num_odd_steps`) is used for the bridges
below. The **3x+1 Conjecture** asserts
that for each positive integer `n` some iterate `TрхЈ(n)` equals `1`, i.e. every orbit on the positive
integers reaches the cycle `{1, 2}` (`T 1 = 2`, `T 2 = 1`). We do not name the conjecture; where it
is needed it is written inline as `Рѕђ n, 0 < n Рєњ РѕЃ j, T_iter j n = 1` (`CC.T_iter`).

## The 2-adic integers `РёцРѓѓ`: the 3x+1 map and the shift

Both maps extend/live on the domain `РёцРѓѓ = Рёц_[2]` of 2-adic integers, where each is "an even
numerator, halved" (`РёцРѓѓ` is a domain, so halving an even element is unique Рђћ `half`):

* the **3x+1 map** `(1.1)` extends to `TРѓѓ`, with even numerator `x┬и3^{parity x} + parity x`
  (`two_mul_TРѓѓ : 2┬иTРѓѓ x = numer x`); it agrees with the integer map on `РёЋ Ріѓ РёцРѓѓ`
  (`TРѓѓ_natCast : TРѓѓ РєЉn = РєЉ(CC.T n)`).
* the **2-adic shift map** `(1.2)` `S(x) = (x-1)/2` for `x РЅА 1`, `S(x) = x/2` for `x РЅА 0`, with even
  numerator `x - parity x` (`two_mul_S : 2┬иS x = x - parity x`). It deletes the lowest binary digit:
  `S(РѕЉ bрхб2РЂ▒) = РѕЉ bрхбРѓіРѓЂ2РЂ▒`, equivalently `x = parity x + 2┬и(S x)` (`parity_add_two_mul_S`); on
  `РёЋ Ріѓ РёцРѓѓ` it is `n Рєд Рїіn/2РїІ` (`S_natCast`).

## Dynamics and conjugacy

Bernstein and Lagarias recall that `TРѓѓ` is **measure-preserving** on `РёцРѓѓ` for the 2-adic (Haar,
normalised) measure and is **strongly mixing**, hence **ergodic**; this is [Lag85] (the paper's
reference [8]). We define `StronglyMixing` and prove (sorry-free) that it implies ergodicity
(`StronglyMixing.ergodic`); strong mixing of `TРѓѓ` is the single cited `axiom` `TРѓѓ_stronglyMixing`,
from which `TРѓѓ_measurePreserving` and `TРѓѓ_ergodic` are **derived**. *More is true* `(1.3)`: `T` is
topologically conjugate to the shift `S` Рђћ there is a homeomorphism `╬д : РёцРѓѓ Рєњ РёцРѓѓ` with
`╬д Рѕў S Рѕў ╬дРЂ╗┬╣ = T` (`exists_conjugacy`). This `╬д` is the titular **3x+1 conjugacy map**; its explicit
construction (the parity-vector map) is the subject of the later sections. In fact this `╬д` can be
taken **measure-preserving** for the 2-adic measure, so `T` is **metrically conjugate** to `S` Рђћ now
**proved** as `exists_metric_conjugacy` in `BL.MetricConjugacy` (the constructed `╬д` is a 2-adic
isometry, and a surjective isometry of `РёцРѓѓ` preserves the Haar measure); and as the 2-adic shift is
the one-sided Bernoulli `(┬й,┬й)` shift (`S_bernoulli`, cited [Kin09] Рђћ the classical p-adic digit fact,
against the genuine product-measure model `IsBernoulli`), `T` is **Bernoulli** Рђћ also **proved**, as
`TРѓѓ_bernoulli` (`BL.MetricConjugacy`). Thus the only cited `axiom`s among the dynamics are now the
genuinely deep / unconstructed inputs (`TРѓѓ_stronglyMixing` and `S_bernoulli`), per the corpus
literature-axiom policy; the metric conjugacy and Bernoulli conclusions are derived.

## Rigidity of `╬д`: the shift automorphism `V`

`╬д` is determined by `(1.3)` only **up to right-multiplication by an automorphism of `S`**
(`conjugacy_unique`). That automorphism group is `Рёц/2Рёц` ([Hed69, Thm 6.9], [BFK90];
`shiftAut_eq_id_or_V`), generated by the **bit-complement** `V x = -1 - x` (`-1 = Рђд111Рѓѓ`, so `V`
flips every binary digit). We define `V` and prove it is an involution (`V_involutive`) commuting
with `S` (`V_semiconj_S`), with `V РЅа id` (`V_ne_id`) Рђћ i.e. `Aut(S) = {id, V}`; so there are exactly
two conjugacy maps, `╬д` and `╬д Рѕў V`.

## Link to the Collatz parity vectors (`CC.Parity`)

The **inverse** conjugacy map `╬дРЂ╗┬╣` is Lagarias's **parity-vector map** `QРѕъ`: `╬дРЂ╗┬╣ x` packs the
forward parity sequence `k Рєд parity (TРѓѓрхЈ x)` of the `TРѓѓ`-orbit of `x` as its binary digits (the
explicit formula `(1.5)`, `BL.ConjugacyMap.Q`). On `РёЋ Ріѓ РёцРѓѓ` this digit sequence is exactly the
Collatz parity vector of `CC.Parity`: the `k`-th 2-adic parity digit of the orbit of `n` equals the
`k`-th vector entry, `parity (TРѓѓрхЈ РєЉn) = X (TрхЈ n)` (`parity_TРѓѓ_iterate_natCast`), matching both the
`РёЋ`-valued `E_vec` (`parity_TРѓѓ_iterate_eq_E_vec`) and the `Bool` word `V` (`getElem_V_eq_parity`);
the digit count is `num_odd_steps` (`num_odd_steps_eq_sum_parity`). These bridges (resting on
`TРѓѓ_iterate_natCast : TРѓѓрхЈ РєЉn = РєЉ(TрхЈ n)`) make `CC.Parity`'s finite parity vectors the truncations of
`╬дРЂ╗┬╣` (the explicit `QРѕъ` of `(1.5)`, `BL.ConjugacyMap.Q`).

## Contents
* `parity`, `half`, `two_mul_half` Рђћ the parity `x mod 2` and the unique half of an even 2-adic integer.
* `numer`, `even_numer`, `TРѓѓ`, `two_mul_TРѓѓ`, `TРѓѓ_natCast` Рђћ the 3x+1 map on `РёцРѓѓ` extending `(1.1)`.
* `shiftNumer`, `even_shiftNumer`, `S`, `two_mul_S`, `parity_add_two_mul_S`, `S_natCast` Рђћ the shift `(1.2)`.
* `parity_natCast`, `TРѓѓ_iterate_natCast`, `parity_TРѓѓ_iterate_natCast`, `parity_TРѓѓ_iterate_eq_E_vec`,
  `getElem_V_eq_parity`, `num_odd_steps_eq_sum_parity` Рђћ bridges to `CC.Parity`: the 2-adic parity
  digits of the `TРѓѓ`-orbit are the Collatz parity vectors (the `QРѕъ`/`╬дРЂ╗┬╣` truncations).
* `StronglyMixing`, `StronglyMixing.ergodic` Рђћ strong mixing and the (proved) implication to ergodicity.
* `seqShift`, `uniformBool`, `bernoulliSeqMeasure`, `IsBernoulli` Рђћ the one-sided Bernoulli `(┬й,┬й)`
  shift on `РёЋ Рєњ Bool` and the "is a Bernoulli system" predicate.
* `TРѓѓ_stronglyMixing` (cited) РЄњ `TРѓѓ_measurePreserving`, `TРѓѓ_ergodic` (derived): `TРѓѓ`'s 2-adic dynamics.
* `(1.3)` `TРѓѓ` is topologically conjugate to the shift `S` Рђћ now **proved** as `exists_conjugacy`
  in `BL.ConjugacyMap` (via the `qMap` construction), no longer a cited axiom here.
* `S_bernoulli` Рђћ cited [Kin09]: the 2-adic shift `S` is the one-sided Bernoulli `(┬й,┬й)` shift.
* `exists_metric_conjugacy`, `TРѓѓ_bernoulli` Рђћ now **proved** downstream in `BL.MetricConjugacy`
  (the conjugacy `╬д` is measure-preserving, so `T` is metrically conjugate to `S` and `TРѓѓ` is Bernoulli).
* `V`, `V_apply_zero`, `V_involutive`, `parity_V`, `V_semiconj_S`, `V_ne_id` Рђћ the shift automorphism
  `V x = -1 - x` (bit-complement): proved to be an involution flipping parity and commuting with `S`.
* `shiftAut_eq_id_or_V` Рђћ cited: `Aut(S) РЅЁ Рёц/2Рёц = {id, V}`.
* `conjugacy_unique` Рђћ **proved** (general fact about conjugacies, Mathlib only): `╬д` is unique up to
  right-multiplication by `Aut(S)`.

